    narr:generatedFrom "02e090750c8c4279ca7934f7186bf883831d71c7" ;
    narr:narration """This hub tracks Scarlet’s pervasive use of the [rule-of-three](narr:StyleObs_RuleOfThree) as a foundational rhetorical and cognitive primitive. The pattern manifests across multiple scales: as [scaffolding for complex taxonomies](narr:StyleObs_RuleOfThreeTaxonomy), [structural logic for interview outputs](narr:StyleObs_RuleOfThreeOutputs), and [compressed decision heuristics](narr:StyleObs_OneSelector3Markets). The tricolon serves as a recurring cadence for [differentiating directions](narr:StyleObs_RuleOfThree_Direction) and [propagating concepts](narr:StyleObs_RuleOfThree_Propagation) across disparate roles and tools. Beyond simple lists, the pattern is often meta-explicit, appearing as [\"three altitudes of the same primitive\"](narr:StyleObs_AltitudeTaxonomy) or an [author-enforced three-sentence rule](narr:StyleObs_ThreeSentenceRule). While the tricolon is dominant, the idiolect also incorporates [negative anaphoric triads](narr:StyleObs_NegativeParallelism) and [numbered convergences](narr:StyleObs_NumberedConvergence) to build logical inevitability. Recent entries show the pattern evolving into [five-question cadences](narr:StyleObs_FiveQuestionCadence) and more complex [layer-based frameworks](narr:StyleObs_RuleOfThree_Layers), suggesting that while the triad remains the primary unit of compression, the system is expanding to accommodate higher-order structural requirements.""" ;
    narr:covers <https://aswritten.ai/narrative#StyleObs_11> ;
